{"copyright": {"licenseType": "NO", "determinationType": "GOV_PUBLIC_USE_PERMITTED", "thirdPartyContentCondition": "NOT_SET"}, "subjectCategories": ["MAN/SYSTEM TECHNOLOGY AND LIFE SUPPORT"], "exportControl": {"isExportControl": "NO", "ear": "NO", "itar": "NO"}, "created": "2013-08-12T13:35:00.0000000+00:00", "distributionDate": "2014-09-26T18:12:09.6700000+00:00", "center": {"code": "CDMS", "name": "Legacy CDMS", "id": "092d6e0881874968859b972d39a888dc"}, "onlyAbstract": false, "sensitiveInformation": 2, "abstract": "A qualitative theory of supervisory control is outlined wherein the mental models of one or more human operators are related to the knowledge representations within automatic controllers (observers, estimators) and operator decision aids (expert systems, advice-givers). Methods of quantifying knowledge and the calibration of one knowledge representation to another (human, computer, or objective truth) are discussed. Ongoing experiments in the use of decision aids for exploring one's own objective function or exploring system constraints and control strategies are described.", "title": "Getting Mental Models and Computer Models to Cooperate", "stiType": "CONFERENCE_PAPER", "distribution": "PUBLIC", "submittedDate": "2013-08-12T13:35:00.0000000+00:00", "isLessonsLearned": false, "authorAffiliations": [{"sequence": 0, "submissionId": 19850006239, "meta": {"author": {"name": "Sheridan, T. B."}, "organization": {"name": "Massachusetts Inst. of Tech.", "location": "Cambridge, MA, United States"}}, "id": "4a1670ac2bf040cd87ca5de327859ff4"}, {"sequence": 1, "submissionId": 19850006239, "meta": {"author": {"name": "Roseborough, J."}, "organization": {"name": "Massachusetts Inst. of Tech.", "location": "Cambridge, MA, United States"}}, "id": "a79d2d3abf084748b1b07afebf7e5258"}, {"sequence": 2, "submissionId": 19850006239, "meta": {"author": {"name": "Charney, L."}, "organization": {"name": "Massachusetts Inst. of Tech.", "location": "Cambridge, MA, United States